default  
defaultIf scientists constantly talk about uncertainty, often the response of the listener is not necessarily apathy but lapsing into an unhappy situation of not knowing how to proceed, and therefore discounting or dodging th
defaulte problem.  Or some can even get angry when scientists don’t know things.  (Shuckburgh 
defaultet al, 
default2012)
default10.  The way the IPCC reports present uncertainties using ranges of probabilities and assigning confidence levels has also been shown to be problematic.  It
default is highly laudable that the scientists are attempting to quantify the uncertainties
default to help decision making
default, but there may well be a mismatch with public understanding unless these concepts are clearly explained.
default11. For example, research in the USA 
defaultabout
default the communication of the 2007 IPCC reports strongly suggests that there can be a 
defaultbig discrep
default&#xad;
defaultancy between the meaning the IPCC intended, and the con
default&#xad;
defaultclu
default&#xad;
defaultsion people actu
default&#xad;
defaultally drew.  In particular, they found that 
defaultthe public consistently misinterpret the IPCC’s probabilistic statements, and usually in a ‘regressive’ way, or in other words, less extreme than intended 
defaultby 
defaultthe authors of the reports.  So for example, when the I
defaultPCC writes that ‘many changes in the global
default climate system during the 21
defaultst
default century &lt;…&gt; would 
defaultvery likely
default be larger than those observed during the 20
defaultth
default century’, the IPCC intends this to mean more than 90% probability, whereas the typical respondent interpreted this to mean a 65-75% probability. 
default(Bu
defaultdescu et al, 2009)
default12. Other criticisms of the IPCC’s portrayal of uncertainties are that it is too complicated; 
defaulttoo 
defaultconfusing (because the intervals overlap); links numbers to words 
