defaultThere is a growing body of literature suggesting that risk language may be a good, or at least a less bad, way of communicating climate change to 
defaultpolicy makers and 
defaultthe general public.   Many argue that when compared to the messages of disaster or uncertain
defaultty that often surround climate change, 
defaultrisk is far from being a panacea, but it does offer a more sophisticated and apposite language to have the discussion in and a more helpful prism through which to analyse the problem.  
default1
default9
default. One of the arguments in fav
defaultour of using risk language is that for policy makers, it shifts the debate away from what would count as conclusive proof or overwhelming certainty before taking action, towards an analysis of the comparative costs and risks of different policy options (in
defaultcluding doing nothing).  
default20
default. 
defaultAnother is that risk is an essential part of everyday experience, including the worlds of insurance, health and investment.   Many people have to deal with it daily and manage it in different ways: most people in the developed
default world take out house insurance against the low-probability, very high-impact event of a fire.  Patients 
defaultare increasingly familiar with the concept of the risks and benefits of different health treatments
default (
defaultthough they rely on trusted intermediaries to help
default them 
defaultto 
defaultnavigate the risk
default)
default.
default&#xa0;
default 
default 
defaultInvestors constantly use the language of risk, and one top UK banker at HSBC reacted to the 
defaultWG-1 report
default by describing climate change as 
defaultessentially 
defaultan ‘issue of strategic risk management’.  
defaultAnd s
defaultome of the risk assessments people make are on the same timescale as possible climate impacts – for example, taking out a pension policy into which they pay for 40 years. 
default21.  It is certainly the case that risk language is 
defaultnow 
defaultoften 
defaultbeing 
defaultused by politici
defaultans and other science communicators.  By risk language, we mean such 
defaultevery day phrases 
default'taking out an insurance policy',
default 
default‘
defaultloading the dice'
default 
defaultor 'playing Russian roulette with the climate'. 
default&#xa0;
defaultDavid Cameron, Michael Bloomberg and Lord Nick Ste
defaultr
defaultn have all recen
defaulttly used such language as a helpful way of describing the problem and the need to take action. 
default Lord Ste
defaultr
defaultn for example 
defaultargues that sceptics have to 
defaultshow 
defaultthey have high confidence the planet is going to experience only the lower end of possible temperature 
defaultincreases for them to make their case that it is not necessary to take action to minimise climate risks.
default22. 
defaultRisk concepts in a narrow sense of assigning probability levels to adverse consequences are important for 
defaulta 
defaultbetter understanding
default of climate science
default.   For example, c
defaultlimate models can now evaluate how much man-made climate change may have made an extreme weather event like a severe flood 
defaultor drought 
defaultmore likely.  Such risk assessments usually include probability levels, and what degree of confidence sc
defaultientists have in their findings.   
default23.  However, even though 
defaultrisk 
defaultlanguage 
defaultand concepts 
defaultshould be 
defaultgenerally 
defaultwelcomed, a number of caveats should be made.  
defaultFirst, some metaphors work better than others, and need to be constantly tested.  ‘Loading the dice
default’ for example, has been shown to work well in the USA, but not so well in the UK where the practice of playing dice is not so widespread.  (Shuckburgh
default et al
default, 2012)
defaultSecondly, there is little research done with focus groups on how 
defaultthey react to risk language and concepts about climate change, in terms of understanding, engagement and behaviour change.  
defaultIntuitively 
defaultmany observers may 
defaultfeel that risk language 
defaultw
defaultould work with a wider audience, who are accustomed to risk from the worlds 
defaultof insurance, betting, health and investment. However, there's a need to test this more. 
default&#xa0;
defaultMoreover, many people may find the numerical assignment of probabilities to possible risks difficult to understand or use as a basis for action. 
defaultThirdly, it 
defaultundersta
defaultndable that the authors of report on the physical science
default (WG-1) 
defaultsh
defaultied
default away from using risk language.
default&#xa0;
default 
defaultThey argue that they prefer to use 
default‘
defaultlikelihoods
default’
default as it is a more neutral and quantifiable language; they say risk on the other hand is a more qualitative
default language and implies only bad outcomes whereas some outcomes from climate change may be beneficial to a limited extent.
default&#xa0;
default2
default4
default. 
defaultHowever, t
defaulthere is already evidence that 
defaultthe Working Group Two 
default(WG-2) 
defaultreport on climate impacts will probably have much more risk l
defaultanguage in it, as the IPCC 
default2012 
